In this article, concepts of TET and main error tunnel (MET), both corresponding to a trajectory generator as introduced in Ref. 20, are considered. An example of generated trajectories is shown in Figure 2. The advantages of exploiting trajectory generator are as follows:


guarantee of limitation of the tracking error (for each point of the main path) to an assumed value;

high resistance to wind gusts which temporarily excess acceptable limits of the used control algorithm;

increase of parametric robustness of the controller;

low-level complexity of the control algorithm.
The trajectory generator exploiting TET and MET divides the control task into a main part and a current part. The main part of the task requires maintaining the position of the airship within MET (i.e. position error lower than δM), while tracking the segment AB¯ (Figure 2) in the three-dimensional space. The permitted error is defined by a cylinder of height |AB¯| and radius δM (MET). The current task demands tracking temporary trajectory, which is described by a time-dependent spatial curve of a third-order polynomial form. The temporary trajectory is also surrounded by errors' temporary tunnel with radius of δT.
Figure 2.
Example of generated trajectories.

Because of the high level of complexity of the model, control parameters were chosen using multi-criteria genetic algorithm implemented in Matlab© software with the Genetic Algorithm and Direct Search Toolbox©. The set of minimized criteria contains five components, namely:


three average position errors along the directions of axes of the global coordinate system;

length of the path remaining to reach the end point of the main trajectory after allowable time;

number of generated temporary trajectories.
During the test, main trajectory was described as a segment with a starting point X0 = [300 50 −80]m and an ending point X1 = [500 −50 −50]m, with TET radius δT = 9 m and MET radius δM = 10 m. For t0 = 0, the airship was placed at the origin of frame E and it was oriented same as the global frame. Additionally, all the velocities were equal to zero. The simulation time was 700 s, which resulted from a need of the airship to reach the main trajectory, but also prevented it from full realization of the trajectory. The airship parameters are based on Ref. 21 which describes AS500 airship by Airspeed Airships. Main airship parameters include: length = 7.8 m, maximum diameter = 1.9 m, volume = 15 m3 and useful load = 3.5 kg.
